  title: In Response to Tang's Commissioner Xueh Zongkuan's Letter
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the twenty-second year of Zhenguan, my late king entered court to receive the imperial edict from Emperor Taizong himself. The edict declared: 'I now march against Goguryeo, not for any other reason than to take pity on you Silla, caught between two nations, suffering endless invasion with no season of peace. I covet neither your mountains and lands, nor do I lack jade and silk or maidens. When I bring order to both kingdoms, all lands south of Pyongyang and Baekje territory shall be given to Silla for your eternal peace.' With these instructions, he granted us the timeline for war, and our people heard the imperial grace—each household gathered strength, each family prepared to serve.

    Yet before the great enterprise could conclude, Emperor Taizong passed. The current emperor ascended the throne and continued his predecessor's benevolence, bestowing upon us even greater grace than before. Our brothers and sons wore crimson robes and purple belts, receiving honors unknown in ancient times. We vowed that though our bodies crumble to dust and our bones scatter, we would gladly exhaust ourselves in service, and even if our blood stained the fields, we would repay one ten-thousandth of the imperial kindness.

    In the fifth year of Xianqing, the sage emperor, moved by the former emperor's unfinished will, sent forth fleets and deployed generals with vast naval forces. Though my late king's years had weakened him beyond marching strength, moved by memory of past kindness, he struggled to the border and dispatched his loyal commanders to receive the great army. Our forces sang in harmony east and west; land and water armies advanced together. Scarcely had the navy entered the river mouth when the land army already crushed the great rebels. Both forces reached the capital, and we jointly brought order to one kingdom.

    After the conquest, my late king and Commander Su worked to stabilize the realm. Ten thousand Han soldiers remained, while Silla sent my brother Intae with seven thousand troops to garrison Xiongzhen. But when the great army withdrew, the traitor Fuksin rose in Gangxi, gathered remnant forces, and besieged the garrison city. He breached the outer palisades, seized all military supplies, attacked the city again and nearly took it. He built four siege fortifications nearby, cutting off all passage to the garrison. I led troops to break the siege, shattered all four rebel strongholds, rescued them from peril, and resupplied the garrison so thoroughly that ten thousand Han soldiers were spared the tiger's jaws and the starving garrison never descended to cannibalism.

    By year six, Fuksin's followers multiplied. He seized lands east of the river. One thousand Han soldiers from Xiongzhen marched to fight but were defeated—not one returned. After this defeat, Xiongzhen's pleas for reinforcement came daily. Though Silla suffered epidemics that made raising troops difficult, we could not refuse their urgent appeals. We dispatched forces to surround Juryuseong, but the rebels, knowing our numbers were small, attacked fiercely and inflicted heavy losses. We withdrew in defeat, and suddenly all cities of the south rose in rebellion, all submitting to Fuksin. Emboldened, Fuksin again besieged the garrison city and severed the salt supply route to Xiongzhen. We quickly recruited strong men to secretly deliver salt through hidden passes, sustaining their survival.

    In the sixth month, my late king passed away. We completed his funeral rites, but not having removed mourning garments, we could not answer the imperial summons to send troops north. When Commissioner Liu Demin arrived with imperial orders to supply Pyongyang with grain, messengers came from Xiongzhen describing the garrison's desperate isolation. Commissioner Liu and I conferred, saying: 'If we send grain to Pyongyang first, the Xiongzhen route will be cut. Should Xiongzhen's route be severed, the Han garrison will fall to the rebels.' So Commissioner Liu and I led troops to first attack Wongsan fortress. Once it fell, we built a fort at Xiongzhen to open the supply route. By December, Xiongzhen's grain was exhausted. We faced an impossible choice—send to Xiongzhen and risk violating imperial orders, or send to Pyongyang and starve the garrison. So we sent the weak and elderly to Xiongzhen while preparing strong troops for Pyongyang. But the grain shipment encountered snow; all soldiers and horses perished, scarcely one in a hundred returning.

    In the first month of year two of Longsuo, Commissioner Liu, along with Silla's Two Rivers Commander Kim Yushin and others, transported grain to Pyongyang. Torrential rains lasted a month; bitter snow and freezing cold killed men and horses—the grain could not reach its destination. The great army wished to withdraw, and Silla's forces too fell back, their grain exhausted. Soldiers starved in the cold, their hands and feet frostbitten; the dead along the road could not be counted. At Hu'lu River, Goguryeo cavalry pursued, forming ranks on the shore. Our exhausted soldiers, fearing the enemy would catch us on the far bank, forded first and clashed. After brief combat, the rebel army disintegrated, and we withdrew our forces.

    Before even a month had passed, Xiongzhen repeatedly requested grain—tens of thousands of bushels sent south to them, north to Pyongyang. Tiny Silla supplied both, exhausting our people and killing all our cattle and horses. Farms missed their planting season; harvests failed. Our stored grain was transported away entirely. Our people lacked even tree bark to eat, while Xiongzhen's Han soldiers had surplus. The garrison soldiers, long separated from home, wore tattered clothes without even a single whole garment. Silla encouraged our people to weave and sent new garments.

    Governor Liu Renyan held his lonely fortress, surrounded entirely by enemies, constantly relieved by Silla. Ten thousand Han soldiers ate Silla's provisions for four years. Their bones were born in Han lands, yet their flesh depended wholly on Silla. Though the imperial grace is boundless, Silla's loyal service surely deserves consideration.

    In year three of Longsuo, Commander Sun Renshi led relief forces to the garrison; Silla mobilized troops and supplies to fight Baekje together. At Juryuseong, a thousand Japanese ships arrived to aid Baekje, anchored at Baisha. Baekje elite cavalry guarded the shore. Silla's skilled cavalry served as the Han vanguard, broke the enemy formation, and Juryuseong lost heart and surrendered.

    With the south secured, we turned north against Goguryeo. Only Renxun fortress resisted, so both armies combined forces but could not breach it. Silla wished to withdraw, but General Du said: 'Imperial orders state that after conquering the enemy, we shall swear alliance together. Though Renxun has not surrendered, we may now take the oath.' But Silla objected: 'Imperial orders require conquest first, then alliance. Renxun has not surrendered, so we cannot claim victory is complete. Moreover, Baekje is treacherous and fickle. Though we swear now, we fear future regret.' We petitioned to postpone the oath.

    In year one of Linde, stern imperial orders rebuked our refusal. We were forced to send men to Xiongzheng to erect an altar and swear alliance, making that place our mutual border. Though this oath was against our wishes, we dared not disobey. We also built an altar at Lishan, and before imperial envoy Liu Renyan, we drank blood together, calling mountains and rivers as witnesses, drawing boundaries and establishing our eternal frontier. Our people settled and pursued their livelihoods.

    In year two of Qianfeng, hearing that Grand Commander Duke of Yingguo was attacking Liaodong, I went to Hanseongju and gathered troops at the border. Silla forces could not enter alone, so we first sent scouts and dispatched three successive boat teams to observe the great army. The scouts returned saying the great army had not yet reached Pyongyang but was attacking Goguryeo's seven-fold fortress to open the road. We expected them hourly, and the fortress was nearly taken when the Duke's messenger Jiangxhen arrived, saying: 'By the Grand Commander's order, Silla need not attack. Proceed quickly to Pyongyang for supplies and meeting.' We went to Shuigu fortress when we heard the great army had already withdrawn, so our forces returned.

    In year three of Qianfeng, we sent Great Supervisor Kim Boga to sea to receive the Duke's orders to concentrate Silla forces at Pyongyang. In the fifth month, General Liu arrived to deploy our troops northward. I went to Hanseongju to inspect the forces. Now all barbarian and Han armies gathered at Sheishui. General Nan Jian led out troops to decide one battle. Silla cavalry alone served as vanguard, first breaking the great formation, causing Pyongyang to lose heart. After this, the Duke summoned five hundred of Silla's cavalry to enter the city gate first, thereby breaking Pyongyang and achieving great victory.

    Our soldiers said: 'After nine years of campaign, exhausting our strength, we have finally brought order to both kingdoms—a hope cherished through generations now realized. Surely Silla will receive the imperial grace of fulfilled loyalty, and our people will receive rewards for their service.' Yet the Duke leaked words that 'Silla failed to meet the military deadline and must surely be punished.' Hearing this, our soldiers' fear redoubled. The victorious generals and commanders were recorded for court, already reaching the capital, when suddenly the Duke announced 'Silla has no merit.' The generals returned, and our people trembled anew.

    Biryeol fortress, once Silla's, was held by Goguryeo for thirty years. When we retook it, we settled our people there and posted officials. Yet the Duke took this city and returned it to Goguryeo. From suppressing Baekje through conquering Goguryeo, Silla gave exhaustive loyalty without betraying our great neighbor. What crime deserves abandonment in a single day? Though we endure such injustice, our hearts remain forever loyal.

    In year one of Zongzhang, Baekje moved the boundary markers at our oath site, seized our lands, seduced our slaves, and enticed our people to hide in their territory. Repeatedly we sought their return; they never came. They circulated rumors that 'the great nation repairs ships, claiming to attack Japan, yet truly plans to crush Silla.' Our people heard and feared. Baekje women married to our officials like Park Doyu plotted with them to steal our weapons and raid our territories. The plot was discovered; we executed Doyu, and their scheme failed.

    In the sixth month of year one of Xianheng, Goguryeo rebelled and killed all Han officials. Silla immediately sought to raise troops and reported to Xiongzhen: 'Goguryeo has rebelled and must be struck. We are both the emperor's servants; we must jointly punish these traitors. Military action requires council—please send officials to deliberate together.' Baekje's commander came, and we agreed to exchange hostages between our two garrisons to prevent mutual suspicion. We sent Kim Donyu to Xiongzhen while Baekje's Sumichanggui and others proceeded there to exchange hostages. Baekje consented, yet secretly massed troops. Upon reaching their city, they attacked in darkness.

    In the seventh month, envoy Kim Heumchun arrived and reviewed boundary maps. All Baekje's former lands were to be returned. But the Yellow River never became a ribbon, nor the Great Mountain a whetstone. In three or four years, we gave and lost repeatedly while Silla's people lost all hope. They said: 'Silla and Baekje are ancient enemies. Seeing Baekje's state, one kingdom will establish itself; within a century, our descendants face obliteration. Silla is now but the empire's province—we cannot be divided into two kingdoms. Let us be one family and end all future suffering.' In the ninth month of last year, we recorded the facts and sent envoys to memorialize the throne, but they were swept back to sea. We sent again, but the messages could not reach. Subsequently, harsh winds and violent waves prevented any communication. Meanwhile, Baekje memorialized that 'Silla has rebelled.'

    Silla lost the favor of noble ministers and suffered Baekje's calumnies. We erred in every direction and failed to demonstrate our loyalty. Such slanders daily reach imperial ears, while our unwavering devotion has never once been heard. Your envoy Linrun has arrived, and I receive your letter. You braved wind and waves crossing distant seas—proper etiquette would send envoys to meet you at the border with cattle and wine. Yet dwelling in this distant place, we failed in ceremony and reception. Please forgive us. Yet reading your letter, you claim 'Silla has already rebelled.' This is not the truth, and I am stricken with fear. I hesitate to defend myself lest I seem mockingly evasive, yet silence seems complicit in misfortune.

    Today I lay bare our grievances: Silla has never rebelled. The great empire neither sends a single envoy to ask the reason nor inquires of our cause, yet mobilizes tens of thousands of troops to destroy our nest. Tower ships fill the azure sea; smaller vessels line the river mouth. It rescues that Xiongzhen, destroys this Silla. When we fought to end two kingdoms, we followed the empire's guidance. Now that the wild beasts are gone, we face the hunter's knife.

    Baekje, remnant rebels, received the generous rewards that Yongchi once enjoyed. Silla, loyal to the empire, now suffers the fate of Ding Gong. Though the sun turns back its light, the sunflower still turns its heart toward the sun.

    Commander, you possess the brilliance of a hero and the talents of generals and ministers. You embody the seven virtues and have studied all nine schools of learning. If you execute heaven's punishment on the guiltless, the great army departs without first inquiring of the cause. Moved by your letter, I dare present our truth: Silla has not rebelled. I implore you to consider carefully and present this memorial fully to the throne.
