  - key: ''
    value: Duke of Yingguo refers to Li Shiji, the Tang's supreme commander against Goguryeo, who held the title of Duke of Yingguo.
  - key: ''
    value: General Nan Jian was the Goguryeo general who held power at the time and was the son of the famous Yeon Gaesomun.
  - key: ''
    value: The allusion to Yongchi refers to a Han dynasty minister who betrayed his lord but was later shown mercy by Liu Bang, who attributed this to Yongchi serving his previous master with loyalty.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Ding Gong recalls another Han figure who showed mercy to Liu Bang when Liu was in peril but was later executed by Liu, who considered such mercy disloyal.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The seven virtues (七德) are: benevolence, righteousness, propriety, wisdom, trustworthiness, courage, and strictness.'
  - key: ''
    value: The nine schools (九流) refer to the classical division of philosophical and scholarly traditions in ancient China.
